metadata.name: Memo #113
metadata.description:
Memo is a abstract expression of memories written on small pieces of paper, pictures of important moments or a reminder of all the things You have forgotten.

Memo is created with P5JS. Large number of rectangles are packed in loops to the canvas with a random rectangle packing algorithm with simple collision detection. 
The looped area varies from 1 vertical or horizontal rectangle to 8x8 grid. Packed area is created with simple random walking grid loop.
60+ color palettes are handpicked and they can appear reversed. 
One random palette is picked for each piece and p5js.noise() drives the colors, size and angle on the rects with lots of attributes.

Click 'n' to add white noise.
Click 's' to save image as jpeg.

Click '1' to 1x pixelDensity(3600 x 6400 or 6400 x 3600 px - default).
Click '2' to 2x pixelDensity(7200 x 12800 or 12800 x 7200 px).

VGA 2022 / CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: Fax Abstraction #104
metadata.description:
The work was created from neurally generated with Latent Diffusion pictorial abstractions, which I was inspired by the work of Gerhard Richter.
They were further hybridized in the spirit of pointillism and Yayoi Kusama and the vintage fax art aesthetic.
Therefore, this work is about the friendship of different artistic styles coexisting together : )

Thanks Yulikolay for help in its creation!

metadata.name: maelstrom3 #2
metadata.description:
This was a bit of technical challenge for me as it's the first piece I've done that heavily integrates both the p5js and hydra libraries. I've created a couple pieces with a bit of either code as an addition but this one required the structure of hydra to display the p5js piece, essentially.

A portion of the price of this piece will go to both the Processing foundation and Hydra's inventor, as well a 10% share of any resale profits for the initial minter.

This piece rewards about 5 minutes attention as it won't be in a "mature" state until the canvas is mostly covered with rectangles. The illusion of depth was made possible by some assistance from the chroma.js library, which really is something of a magic bullet when you begin to fully use it.

Come with me, into a vortex of swirling dollar signs, hurtling forward with no safety net.

metadata.name: Symbolic Disturbance #116
metadata.description:
Visions of fantastic. 

Driven by nature’s unruly force and taking inspiration from my home country’s pagan heritage.

Like many, I tend to overthink even the simplest things by a lot, and in response to those feelings I tried to create something that would have both the airiness of doubts and solidity of certainty.

The work is fully generated by code, sweat and <3.

* * *

Saving high resolution images (works in full screen mode):
:: Press “1” for 2K image
:: Press “2” for 4K image
:: Press “3” for 8K image

metadata.name: Reading a book #35
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.
